{"questionId":"9071971","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Bromine can form the bromate(V) ion, BrO<sub>3</sub><sup>−</sup>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Bromate(V) ions oxidize iron(II) ions, Fe<sup>2+</sup>, to iron(III) ions, Fe<sup>3+</sup>.</p>\n<p>Deduce the equation for this redox reaction.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>BrO<sub>3</sub><sup>−</sup> (aq)&nbsp;+ 6Fe<sup>2+</sup> (aq) + 6H<sup>+</sup> (aq) → Br<sup>−</sup> (aq) + 3H<sub>2</sub>O (l)&nbsp;+ 6Fe<sup>3+</sup> (aq) ✔</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9071971","referenceCode":"18N.2.hl.TZ0.3d.ii","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Bromate(V) ions oxidize iron(II) ions, Fe2+, to iron(III) ions, Fe3+. Deduce the equation for this redox reaction.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 9: Redox processes","9.1 Oxidation and reduction","Core","Topic 9: Redox processes"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}